03814nam a22006015i 9780226483726DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264837267 a10.7208/97802264837262doi  a(DE-B1597)522646  a(OCoLC)1011497375  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML3800b.G18 2018 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a781.172231 aGallope, Michael, eauthor.10aDeep Refrains :bMusic, Philosophy, and the Ineffable /cMichael Gallope. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b10 halftones, 20 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMusical Examples -- tFigures -- tIntroduction -- tPrelude. A Paradox of the Ineffable -- tInterlude. Wittgenstein's Silence -- tConclusion: A Paradox of the Vernacular -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe often say that music is ineffable, that it does not refer to anything outside of itself. But if music, in all its sensuous flux, does not mean anything in particular, might it still have a special kind of philosophical significance?   In Deep Refrains, Michael Gallope draws together the writings of Arthur Schopenhauer, Friedrich Nietzsche, Ernst Bloch, Theodor Adorno, Vladimir Jankélévitch, Gilles Deleuze, and Félix Guattari in order to revisit the age-old question of music's ineffability from a modern perspective. For these nineteenth- and twentieth-century European philosophers, music's ineffability is a complex phenomenon that engenders an intellectually productive sense of perplexity. Through careful examination of their historical contexts and philosophical orientations, close attention to their use of language, and new interpretations of musical compositions that proved influential for their work, Deep Refrains forges the first panoptic view of their writings on music. Gallope concludes that music's ineffability is neither a conservative phenomenon nor a pious call to silence. Instead, these philosophers ask us to think through the ways in which music's stunning force might address, in an ethical fashion, intricate philosophical questions specific to the modern world.      aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 4aAdorno, Theodor. 4aAesthetics of Music. 4aBloch, Ernst. 4aComparative Literature. 4aDeleuze, Gilles. 4aGuattari, Félix. 4aHegel, Georg Wilhelm Friedrich. 4aJankélévitch, Vladimir. 4aSchopenhauer, Arthur. 4aThe Ineffable. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226483726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226483726.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles